Looks like you&#39;re trying to override the prototype method using a closure, which is generally a smart way to do it, only it&#39;s not done exactly right in your snippet. Consider a simplified version of the construct you&#39;ve used:

    fabric.Canvas.prototype.add = (function A(argA) {
      return function B(argsB){
        //..
      }
    })(fabric.Canvas.prototype.add)

Here you&#39;re invoking `function A`, passing `fabric.Canvas.prototype.add` as an argument. This creates a closure, preserving the original `fabric.Canvas.prototype.add` in `function A`&#39;s scope. Then, you&#39;re assigning whatever `function A` returns to the `fabric.Canvas.prototype.add`. In effect, this translates to

    fabric.Canvas.prototype.add = function B(argsB){ /*... */}

only now `function B` has access to the original `fabric.Canvas.prototype.add`.

Returning to your snippet, notice how you&#39;re expecting `object, callback` as arguments of `function A` and no arguments in `function B` - this does nothing useful (see above). Moreover, when you&#39;re calling `this.add()` - this is the place where you&#39;re supposed to call the _original_ `add()` not the _new one_. Otherwise, you&#39;re getting an infinite recursion.

---
Having said that, here&#39;s the right way to do this:

    fabric.Canvas.prototype.add = (function(originalFn) {
      return function(...args) {
        originalFn.call(this, ...args)
        args[0].animate(&#39;top&#39;, &#39;100&#39;, {
            onChange: this.renderAll.bind(this),
            duration: 1000,
            easing: fabric.util.ease.easeOutElastic,
            onComplete: function () {
            }
        });
        return this
      };
    })(fabric.Canvas.prototype.add);

Note the usage of rest parameters `...args`, since `add()` is supposed to handle multiple objects as the arguments. I&#39;m calling `animate()` on the first passed object, so you might want to change that.

Also, don&#39;t forget that the original `add()` is supposed to return the instance of `fabric.Canvas` for the chaining to work, hence `return this` at the end.

